  "prompt": "What is the integration of \u221asinx?",
  "response": "To find the integral of \\(\\sqrt{\\sin x}\\), we can approach it using substitution and trigonometric identities. However, it's worth noting that this integral is non-trivial and does not have a simple elementary antiderivative. We generally express the result in terms of elliptic integrals.\n\nLet's outline the process:\n\n1. **Substitution:**\n   Let \\( u = \\sin x \\), then \\( du = \\cos x \\, dx \\).\n\n2. Consider the integral:\n   \\[\n   \\int \\sqrt{\\sin x} \\, dx = \\int \\sqrt{u} \\frac{du}{\\cos x}\n   \\]\n\n3. Use the Pythagorean identity on \\( \\cos x \\) with \\( \\sin x = u \\):\n   \\[\n   \\cos x = \\sqrt{1 - u^2}\n   \\]\n\nThis changes the integral to:\n   \\[\n   \\int \\sqrt{u} \\frac{du}{\\sqrt{1 - u^2}}\n   \\]\n\n4. Simplify and separate the integral:\n   \\[\n   \\int \\frac{\\sqrt{u}}{\\sqrt{1 - u^2}} \\, du\n   \\]\n\nThis integral can be evaluated in terms of a beta function or elliptic integrals due to its complexity. In general form, elliptic integrals are used to express such integral.\n\nSo, the integral of \\(\\sqrt{\\sin x}\\) with respect to \\(x\\) is expressed as an elliptic integral:\n\\[\n\\int \\sqrt{\\sin x} \\, dx\n\\]\n\nTo summarize, while there is no simple elementary antiderivative for \\(\\sqrt{\\sin x}\\), it is typically expressed using special functions, particularly the elliptic integrals.",
